# Longest Increasing Subsequence (LIS)

Here are a few implementations with different approaches:

## 1. **Dynamic Programming Approach (O(n²))**

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

std::vector<int> longestIncreasingSubsequence(const std::vector<int>& arr) {
    if (arr.empty()) return {};

    int n = arr.size();
    std::vector<int> dp(n, 1);           // dp[i] = length of LIS ending at i
    std::vector<int> parent(n, -1);      // to track the sequence

    // Build dp array
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
            if (arr[j] < arr[i] && dp[j] + 1 > dp[i]) {
                dp[i] = dp[j] + 1;
                parent[i] = j;
            }
        }
    }

    // Find index of maximum length
    int maxIndex = std::max_element(dp.begin(), dp.end()) - dp.begin();

    // Reconstruct the sequence
    std::vector<int> result;
    int idx = maxIndex;
    while (idx != -1) {
        result.push_back(arr[idx]);
        idx = parent[idx];
    }

    std::reverse(result.begin(), result.end());
    return result;
}
```

## 2. **Binary Search Approach (O(n log n))**

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

std::vector<int> longestIncreasingSubsequence(const std::vector<int>& arr) {
    if (arr.empty()) return {};

    std::vector<int> lis;
    std::vector<int> parent(arr.size(), -1);
    std::vector<int> lis_indices;

    for (int i = 0; i < arr.size(); i++) {
        auto it = std::lower_bound(lis.begin(), lis.end(), arr[i]);
        int pos = it - lis.begin();

        if (pos == lis.size()) {
            lis.push_back(arr[i]);
            lis_indices.push_back(i);
        } else {
            lis[pos] = arr[i];
            lis_indices[pos] = i;
        }

        parent[i] = (pos > 0) ? lis_indices[pos - 1] : -1;
    }

    // Reconstruct sequence
    std::vector<int> result;
    int idx = lis_indices.back();
    while (idx != -1) {
        result.push_back(arr[idx]);
        idx = parent[idx];
    }

    std::reverse(result.begin(), result.end());
    return result;
}
```

## 3. **Simple Version (Returns only length)**

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

int longestIncreasingSubsequenceLength(const std::vector<int>& arr) {
    if (arr.empty()) return 0;

    int n = arr.size();
    std::vector<int> dp(n, 1);

    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
            if (arr[j] < arr[i]) {
                dp[i] = std::max(dp[i], dp[j] + 1);
            }
        }
    }

    return *std::max_element(dp.begin(), dp.end());
}
```

## Usage Example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> numbers = {10, 9, 2, 5, 3, 7, 101, 18};

    auto result = longestIncreasingSubsequence(numbers);

    std::cout << "LIS: ";
    for (int num : result) {
        std::cout << num << " ";
    }
    std::cout << "\nLength: " << result.size() << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

**Output:**
```
LIS: 2 3 7 101 
Length: 4
```

## Comparison:

| Approach | Time | Space | Returns |
|----------|------|-------|---------|
| DP (O(n²)) | O(n²) | O(n) | Sequence |
| Binary Search | O(n log n) | O(n) | Sequence |
| Length Only | O(n²) | O(n) | Length |

Choose the **binary search approach** for better performance with larger datasets!

# Find Second Highest Number in Array

Here's a clean and efficient function:

```javascript
function findSecondHighest(arr) {
  // Remove duplicates and sort in descending order
  const uniqueSorted = [...new Set(arr)].sort((a, b) => b - a);

  // Return second element if it exists
  return uniqueSorted.length > 1 ? uniqueSorted[1] : null;
}

// Test with your array
const numbers = [11, 2, 31, 7, 15];
console.log(findSecondHighest(numbers)); // Output: 15
```

## Alternative Solutions

**Option 2: Using Math.max() (handles duplicates)**
```javascript
function findSecondHighest(arr) {
  const max = Math.max(...arr);
  const secondMax = Math.max(...arr.filter(n => n !== max));

  return secondMax === -Infinity ? null : secondMax;
}

console.log(findSecondHighest([11, 2, 31, 7, 15])); // Output: 15
```

**Option 3: Single pass (most efficient for large arrays)**
```javascript
function findSecondHighest(arr) {
  let highest = -Infinity;
  let secondHighest = -Infinity;

  for (let num of arr) {
    if (num > highest) {
      secondHighest = highest;
      highest = num;
    } else if (num > secondHighest && num !== highest) {
      secondHighest = num;
    }
  }

  return secondHighest === -Infinity ? null : secondHighest;
}

console.log(findSecondHighest([11, 2, 31, 7, 15])); // Output: 15
```

## Comparison

| Method | Pros | Cons |
|--------|------|------|
| **Option 1** | Clean, removes duplicates | O(n log n) - slower |
| **Option 2** | Simple logic | Multiple iterations, filters array |
| **Option 3** | **O(n) - Most efficient** | Slightly more code |

**Recommendation:** Use **Option 1** for simplicity or **Option 3** for better performance with large arrays.

