# C++ Version

Here are a few ways to rewrite this code in C++:

## Option 1: Using `std::sort` (Most Similar to Java)
```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <string>

bool isAnagram(std::string str1, std::string str2) {
    std::sort(str1.begin(), str1.end());
    std::sort(str2.begin(), str2.end());
    return str1 == str2;
}
```

## Option 2: Using `std::map` (Frequency Count)
```cpp
#include <map>
#include <string>

bool isAnagram(const std::string& str1, const std::string& str2) {
    if (str1.length() != str2.length()) {
        return false;
    }

    std::map<char, int> charCount;

    for (char c : str1) {
        charCount[c]++;
    }

    for (char c : str2) {
        if (charCount[c] == 0) {
            return false;
        }
        charCount[c]--;
    }

    return true;
}
```

## Option 3: Using `std::unordered_map` (More Efficient)
```cpp
#include <unordered_map>
#include <string>

bool isAnagram(const std::string& str1, const std::string& str2) {
    if (str1.length() != str2.length()) {
        return false;
    }

    std::unordered_map<char, int> charCount;

    for (char c : str1) {
        charCount[c]++;
    }

    for (char c : str2) {
        if (charCount[c]-- == 0) {
            return false;
        }
    }

    return true;
}
```

## Comparison

| Option | Time Complexity | Space Complexity | Notes |
|--------|-----------------|------------------|-------|
| 1 (sort) | O(n log n) | O(1) | Most concise, similar to Java |
| 2 (map) | O(n) | O(k) | k = unique characters |
| 3 (unordered_map) | O(n) | O(k) | Best average performance |

**Recommendation:** Use **Option 1** for simplicity or **Option 3** for better performance.

